{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"35ba2cb4-d177-4a06-953f-e44572d98875","content":"For .NET 10 on Linux with native frames, **`perf`** is the best tool — `dotnet-trace` (EventPipe) doesn't reliably capture native call stacks. Here's the workflow:\n\n### 1. Enable managed frame resolution\n\nSet these environment variables **before** starting your service:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_PerfMapEnabled=1        # writes /tmp/perf-<pid>.map\nexport DOTNET_EnableWriteXorExecute=0 # allows perf to read JIT'd code\n```\n\n### 2. Record with `perf`\n\n```bash\n# DWARF unwinding gives the most reliable native stacks\nperf record -g --call-graph dwarf -p <PID> -- sleep 30\n```\n\nUse `dwarf` (not `fp`) because .NET JIT'd code and many native libraries omit frame pointers.\n\n### 3. Resolve & visualize\n\n```bash\n# Text dump\nperf script > out.perf\n\n# Flame graph (most actionable view)\nperf script | stackcollapse-perf.pl | flamegraph.pl > flamegraph.svg\n```\n\n*(The FlameGraph scripts are from [Brendan Gregg's repo](https://github.com/brendangregg/FlameGraph).)*\n\n### Key notes\n\n| Concern | Recommendation |\n|---|---|\n| **Large traces** | Add `--freq 99` to reduce overhead while keeping accuracy |\n| **Short-lived CPU bursts** | Use `perf record -a` (system-wide) instead of `-p` |\n| **Container inside VM** | Mount `/tmp` from the host so perf can find the `.map` file |\n| **Kernel stacks too** | Add `-k DWARF` for kernel-side frames |\n\nThis gives you a unified flame graph with managed → native → kernel frames all stitched together.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"01a46ca9-c23e-4d72-9c93-501b75b8698d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting performance traces with native call stacks on a .NET 10 application running on Linux. This is a diagnostics/performance question, not a code change request. I should provide a concise, expert answer.\n\nKey points:\n- .NET 10 on Linux kernel 6.8\n- Root access available\n- High CPU suspected in native code\n- Wants rich trace with native call stacks\n\nThe best approach here is using `dotnet-trace` with the `perf` or `speedscope` format, or using Linux `perf` directly. But for .NET + native combined stacks, the gold standard is:\n\n\nFor native stacks alongside managed code, `perf record` with DWARF call graph unwinding is the most reliable option—I'd enable the managed symbol maps through environment variables so the native profiler can resolve .NET frames too. the best approach is using `perf` with the PerfMap environment variable enabled to capture both native and managed frames together, then recording with `perf record -g` and visualizing the results with FlameGraph or speedscope tools.","outputTokens":1076,"requestId":"C3D0:3A80DA:1C2F43C:1FB0D7D:6A07BF5D"},"id":"d2608bf4-9de8-41fc-860b-ee65387923de","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:03.098Z","parentId":"ec3c3c48-ed41-4a0b-9133-7fcec346b879"}
